Let's write the fixed code:

```
static boolean isSimpleNumber(String s) {
    int len = s.length();
    if (len == 0) {
        return false;
    }
    if (len == 1) {
        return s.charAt(0) >= '0' && s.charAt(0) <= '9';
    }
    if (s.charAt(0) == '0') {
        return false;
    }
    for (int index = 0; index < len; index++) {
        char c = s.charAt(index);
        if (c < '0' || c > '9') {
            return false;
        }
    }
    return true;
}
```

But we can simplify: check all characters are digits, and then ensure no leading zero unless length==1.

Better:

```
static boolean isSimpleNumber(String s) {
    int len = s.length();
    if (len == 0) {
        return false;
    }
    // Check all characters are digits
    for (int index = 0; index < len; index++) {
        char c = s.charAt(index);
        if (c < '0' || c > '9') {
            return false;
        }
    }
    // No leading zero unless it's exactly "0"
    return len == 1 || s.charAt(0) != '0';
}
```

That matches the original logic except fixed for "0".

